Explain how this C++ code works. It takes in three vertices of an image and draws and fills a triangle with the given color.

void triangle(Vec2i t0, Vec2i t1, Vec2i t2, TGAImage &image, TGAColor color) { 
    // sort the vertices, t0, t1, t2 lower−to−upper (bubblesort yay!) 
    if (t0.y>t1.y) std::swap(t0, t1); 
    if (t0.y>t2.y) std::swap(t0, t2); 
    if (t1.y>t2.y) std::swap(t1, t2); 
    int total_height = t2.y-t0.y; 
    for (int y=t0.y; y<=t1.y; y++) { 
        int segment_height = t1.y-t0.y+1; 
        float alpha = (float)(y-t0.y)/total_height; 
        float beta  = (float)(y-t0.y)/segment_height; // be careful with divisions by zero 
        Vec2i A = t0 + (t2-t0)*alpha; 
        Vec2i B = t0 + (t1-t0)*beta; 
        if (A.x>B.x) std::swap(A, B); 
        for (int j=A.x; j<=B.x; j++) { 
            image.set(j, y, color); // attention, due to int casts t0.y+i != A.y 
        } 
    } 
    for (int y=t1.y; y<=t2.y; y++) { 
        int segment_height =  t2.y-t1.y+1; 
        float alpha = (float)(y-t0.y)/total_height; 
        float beta  = (float)(y-t1.y)/segment_height; // be careful with divisions by zero 
        Vec2i A = t0 + (t2-t0)*alpha; 
        Vec2i B = t1 + (t2-t1)*beta; 
        if (A.x>B.x) std::swap(A, B); 
        for (int j=A.x; j<=B.x; j++) { 
            image.set(j, y, color); // attention, due to int casts t0.y+i != A.y 
        } 
    } 
}

This C++ function, named `triangle`, takes in three vertices in the form of `Vec2i` objects (t0, t1, t2), a TGAImage object (image), and a TGAColor object (color). It draws and fills a triangle in the given image by using a scanline algorithm with the specified color.

Let's break down the code:

1. Sort the vertices t0, t1, and t2 by their y-values from lowest to highest using a simple bubble sort:

   ```
   if (t0.y>t1.y) std::swap(t0, t1); 
   if (t0.y>t2.y) std::swap(t0, t2); 
   if (t1.y>t2.y) std::swap(t1, t2);
   ```

2. Calculate the total height of the triangle by finding the difference between the highest and lowest y-value: `int total_height = t2.y-t0.y;`.

3. The code then splits the triangle into two segments, from t0 to t1 and from t1 to t2, and iterates over each segment using two for-loops.

   ```
   for (int y=t0.y; y<=t1.y; y++) {
   ...
   }
   for (int y=t1.y; y<=t2.y; y++) {
   ...
   }
   ```

4. For each segment, calculate the segment height, alpha, and beta values. These are used for interpolating the x-values and drawing horizontal lines inside the triangle.

   ```
   int segment_height = t1.y-t0.y+1;
   float alpha = (float)(y-t0.y)/total_height;
   float beta = (float)(y-t0.y)/segment_height;
   ```

5. Calculate the x-coordinates for both sides of the triangle using alpha and beta, interpolating between t0, t1, and t2.

   ```
   Vec2i A = t0 + (t2-t0)*alpha;
   Vec2i B = t0 + (t1-t0)*beta;
   ```

6. Swap A and B if necessary to ensure that A.x is less than or equal to B.x: `if (A.x>B.x) std::swap(A, B);`.

7. Now, for each value of y, iterate over the x-values from A.x to B.x and set the color at these coordinates in the image.

   ```
   for (int j=A.x; j<=B.x; j++) {
       image.set(j, y, color);
   }
   ```

Overall, this code efficiently fills in the triangle in the image using a scanline algorithm.

