Designing a material system for a game engine in C++ can be broken down into several smaller tasks. Here's a suggested approach to creating a flexible, extendable material system. This overview assumes that you have a general understanding of game development and rendering concepts.

1. Define Material and Shader classes:

First, we need to create a Material class that would represent the material properties and a Shader class representing the shader program.

```cpp
class Material {
public:
    Material();
    ~Material();

    // Methods for setting material properties like color, texture, etc.
    void SetColor(const glm::vec4& color);
    void SetTexture(std::shared_ptr<Texture> texture);
    void SetShader(std::shared_ptr<Shader> shader);

    // Getters
    glm::vec4 GetColor() const;
    std::shared_ptr<Texture> GetTexture() const;
    std::shared_ptr<Shader> GetShader() const;

private:
    glm::vec4 m_Color;
    std::shared_ptr<Texture> m_Texture;
    std::shared_ptr<Shader> m_Shader;
};
```

```cpp
class Shader {
public:
    Shader();
    ~Shader();

    // Methods for loading shader from file or directly setting source code
    bool LoadFromFile(const std::string& vertexPath, const std::string& fragmentPath);
    bool LoadFromSource(const std::string& vertexSource, const std::string& fragmentSource);

    // Methods for handling the shader program
    void Use();
    GLuint GetProgramID() const;

    // Set uniform values for the shader
    void SetInt(const std::string& name, const GLint value) const;
    void SetFloat(const std::string& name, const GLfloat value) const;
    void SetVec2(const std::string& name, const glm::vec2& value) const;
    void SetVec3(const std::string& name, const glm::vec3& value) const;
    void SetVec4(const std::string& name, const glm::vec4& value) const;
    void SetMat4(const std::string& name, const glm::mat4& value) const;

private:
    GLuint m_ProgramID;

    // ... other necessary methods and variables for shaders
};
```

2. Create Mesh Renderer:

Create a MeshRenderer class that would have a reference to a Mesh object and a Material object. It will be responsible for rendering the Mesh using the properties of the Material.

```cpp
class MeshRenderer {
public:
    MeshRenderer(std::shared_ptr<Mesh> mesh, std::shared_ptr<Material> material);
    ~MeshRenderer();

    // Handle rendering process
    void Render(const glm::mat4& model, const glm::mat4& view, const glm::mat4& projection);

private:
    std::shared_ptr<Mesh>     m_Mesh;
    std::shared_ptr<Material> m_Material;
};
```

3. In the MeshRenderer::Render() method, you'll want to gather information from the attached Mesh and Material, and apply this information to the active OpenGL state. This could involve binding the appropriate vertex array, binding the shader program, setting shader uniform values, binding the texture, etc. Then, execute the actual rendering with a call to a function like `glDrawElements`, with the relevant data - such as vertex indices - from the Mesh object.

4. Now, your game objects should be able to have a MeshRenderer component attached to them, which handles rendering the attached Mesh with the attached Material's properties, such as color or texture and using the Shader specified in the Material.

In conclusion, by separating Mesh, Material, and Shader classes, you can create a flexible material system for a game engine in C++. This design allows you to mix and match different materials, textures, and shaders for different game objects seamlessly.

